\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 1. System Architecture\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 Stata functions as an integrated development environment for statistical inquiry, prioritizing command-driven, script-based execution over menu-driven workflows. It operates around the 
\f0\b do-file
\f1\b0 \'97a text-based script recording every data manipulation, estimation, and visualization. This architecture ensures complete reproducibility
\fs32 \super 1
\fs24 \nosupersub .\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 1.1 Data Management and Memory\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\fs24 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 In-Memory Processing:
\f1\b0  Stata operates on a dataset residing in memory. Recent versions utilize "frames" to hold multiple datasets simultaneously
\fs32 \super 2
\fs24 \nosupersub .\uc0\u8232 \u8232 \
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Data Typing:
\f1\b0  Stata enforces rigorous data typing, distinguishing between storage types to manage memory and precision:\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl1
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Integers:
\f1\b0  byte, int, long\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b Real Numbers:
\f1\b0  float, double
\fs32 \super 3
\fs24 \nosupersub .\uc0\u8232 \u8232 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Programmability:
\f1\b0  The core of Stata is extensible. "Official" commands are written in Stata\'92s own coding language (ADO files), allowing users to inspect source code. Stata also utilizes "Mata," a compiled matrix programming language for custom estimators
\fs32 \super 4444
\fs24 \nosupersub .\uc0\u8232 \u8232 \u8232 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 2. Computational Foundations: Precision and Algorithms\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 The accuracy of Stata\'92s statistical results is bounded by the precision of the floating-point arithmetic used to compute them
\fs32 \super 5
\fs24 \nosupersub .\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 2.1 Numerical Precision: Float vs. Double\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\fs24 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Float (Default):
\f1\b0  A 4-byte IEEE 754 single-precision binary floating-point number (approx. 7 decimal digits). Large IDs (e.g., 1234567890) stored as float will suffer truncation error
\fs32 \super 6
\fs24 \nosupersub .\uc0\u8232 \u8232 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b Double:
\f1\b0  An 8-byte IEEE 754 double-precision binary floating-point number (approx. 16 decimal digits)
\fs32 \super 7
\fs24 \nosupersub .\uc0\u8232 \u8232 \
\ls2\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b Internal Calculation:
\f1\b0  Stata performs all internal calculations in 
\f0\b double precision
\f1\b0 , regardless of storage type, to preserve fidelity during intermediate steps (e.g., matrix inversion)
\fs32 \super 8
\fs24 \nosupersub .\uc0\u8232 \u8232 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 2.2 Random Number Generation\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b Algorithm:
\f1\b0  Stata uses the 
\f0\b 64-bit Mersenne Twister (MT64)
\f1\b0\fs32 \super 9
\fs24 \nosupersub .\uc0\u8232 \u8232 \
\ls3\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b Periodicity:
\f1\b0  $2^\{19937\} - 1$
\fs32 \super 10
\fs24 \nosupersub .\uc0\u8232 \u8232 \
\ls3\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b Resolution:
\f1\b0  53-bit resolution for precise uniform random variates
\fs32 \super 11
\fs24 \nosupersub .\uc0\u8232 \u8232 \
\ls3\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b Reproducibility:
\f1\b0  Stata supports version control (e.g., version 13) to revert to older RNG algorithms (KISS32) for backward compatibility
\fs32 \super 12
\fs24 \nosupersub .\uc0\u8232 \u8232 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 2.3 Matrix Inversion Algorithms\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 Stata employs specialized numerical linear algebra routines, primarily via Mata
\fs32 \super 13
\fs24 \nosupersub .\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2 \cf0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Cholesky Decomposition:
\f1\b0  Used for symmetric positive-definite matrices (like covariance matrices). It decomposes matrix $A$ into $LL'$ (where $L$ is lower triangular)
\fs32 \super 14141414
\fs24 \nosupersub .\uc0\u8232 \u8232 \u8232 \
\ls4\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Generalized Inverse (invsym):
\f1\b0  Used when the matrix is singular (rank-deficient). The algorithm sweeps through columns; if a column is linearly dependent on previous ones, the entire row/column is set to zero in the inverse. This automatically handles multicollinearity by omitting variables
\fs32 \super 15
\fs24 \nosupersub .\uc0\u8232 \u8232 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 3. Descriptive Statistics: summarize Logic\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf0 3.1 Mean and Variance Calculation\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b Mean:
\f1\b0  $\\bar\{x\} = \\frac\{\\sum w_i x_i\}\{W\}$ where $W$ is the sum of weights
\fs32 \super 16
\fs24 \nosupersub .\uc0\u8232 \u8232 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Variance:
\f1\b0  $s^2 = \\frac\{1\}\{W-1\} \\sum w_i (x_i - \\bar\{x\})^2$. Stata uses $W-1$ for the unbiased estimator
\fs32 \super 17
\fs24 \nosupersub .\uc0\u8232 \u8232 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b Analytic Weights (aweights):
\f1\b0  Weights are normalized to sum to $N$ (physical observations), treating $w_i$ as inversely proportional to variance
\fs32 \super 18
\fs24 \nosupersub .\uc0\u8232 \u8232 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 3.2 Skewness and Kurtosis\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b Skewness ($g_1$):
\f1\b0  Fisher-Pearson coefficient: $g_1 = \\frac\{m_3\}\{m_2^\{3/2\}\}$
\fs32 \super 19
\fs24 \nosupersub .\uc0\u8232 \u8232 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Kurtosis ($b_2$):
\f1\b0  Stata reports 
\f0\b raw kurtosis
\f1\b0 : $b_2 = \\frac\{m_4\}\{m_2^2\}$. For a normal distribution, $b_2 = 3$
\fs32 \super 20
\fs24 \nosupersub .\uc0\u8232 \u8232 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 3.3 Normality Testing (sktest)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 Uses the D'Agostino-Pearson omnibus test
\fs32 \super 21
\fs24 \nosupersub .\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2 \cf0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls7\ilvl0
\f1 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b Statistic:
\f1\b0  $K^2 = Z(g_1)^2 + Z(b_2)^2$, distributed as $\\chi^2$ with 2 degrees of freedom
\fs32 \super 22
\fs24 \nosupersub .\uc0\u8232 \u8232 \
